{"/service/ndnp/mohi/batch_mohi_boone_ver01/data/sn89066313/00211109609/1910061701/0552.xml":{"full_text":"UNIVERSITY MISSOURIAN\nFRIDAY, JUNE 17, 1910.\nPAGE FOUR\nASSEMBLY DANGE\nCOLUMBIA HALL\nSaturday Night, June 18.\nThis is the first dance held since the\nsummer students have arrived and they\nare all invited to attend.\nYOU WILL HAVE NO ANXIETY\nconcerning funds while away from\nhome if you purchase\nMERCANTILE TRUST CO.\nOR\nAMERICAN EXPRESS CO.\nTraveler's Checks. These checks, though perfectly protecting\nyou from loss, arc the embodiment of simplicity\nWe issue them in denominations of $10. $20, $50 and $100.\nThey can be cashed anywhere in the world. Call and see us for\nfull particulars.\nBOONE COUNTY TRUST CO.\nLack of Exercise During Vacation.\nXow that the school year is nearly\nlit an end, the physical exercises\nwhich are a part of every city school\nprogram are likely to lie ended also,\nmuch to the loss of many little ;irls\nwho are bcneiiiin? by such instruc\ntion. Of course, with freedom from\nstudies and confinement in the school\n-room there comes more general physi\ncal activity, but it is not of the system\natic 'type which has been taught, dur\ning the school year, with the view of\ndeveloping certain muscles and bring\ning into action others infrequently\nused.\nSuch exercises may be continued at\nhome, under the supervision of some\nolder members of the family, and the\nbenefit of the last ten month's work\niwill be lurther extended.\nCrowing girls need the out-of-door\natmosphere. They need to grow into\nstrong, beautiful womanhood. The e.v\ni ercises need not be conliueil to a\ni gymnasium nor taken under the watch-\nfill eye of an athletic instructor. As\nl much good may be done in the back\nyard or in a bedroom witli open win\ndows and father, mother or brother\nmay be the instructor. Care must u\ntaken to see that the little girls do\nnot indulge in the exercises too long\nor too vigorously, especially at lirst.\nHuston Traveler.\nWhat will be your Recrea\ntion during these summer\nmonths?\nAmerican Extravagance.\nOver $lii,tMm.iMMi,oiMi worth of dia\nmonds and other precious stones were\nimported into this country through the\nport of Xew York during the last ten\nmouths. The expectation i that the\nimportation s will increase another\nS2.iHiO.uuo during the present month\nand that the total importations for the\nfiscal year will be at least Sl-l.oou.imu,\nexceeding by SII.imih.imio the greatest\nprevious importations ever r corded.\nThe significant-\" ol these ligures lies\nin the showing that people are not\nonly prosperous enough to spend mil\nlion for articles of personal adorn\nment, but that they have no fear for\nthe future to compel them ;o exercise\nsome of the economies which wore\nmuch in evidence a couple of years\nago. After the latest Wall street de\npression, which seriously crippled gen\neral business by creating an artilical\nshortage of nioiwy. the business of im\nporting precious jewels was the one\nmost immediately affected. There\nwas a sudden and large decline in\ntlie volume ol importations. People\nhad other uses to.' their money than in\nbuying of diamonds.\nIt also illustrates the tendency of\nthe American peojle to react sharp\nly from economy to extravagance the\ninstant that the pressure is off from\nthem and they feel no fears for the\nimmediate future. When times are\nhard, or there is a financial business\ndepression, the average man in the\ncountry feels for the time being some\n'fears for the future and proceeds tit\neconomize sharply. He does not feel\nhall as sure of a retention of em\nployment as he did before, and he\n'knows that the expected advance in\nwages is rot to be forthcoming. This\n1 is one large fact which enables the\nj country to recuperate so quickly\n'from the ctfects ol a depression. The\n'American standard of wages and liv\ning is so high, under ordinary circum\nstances, that there is usually a fair\nmargin for saving, wh'ii ordinary eco-\nSelf Sacrifice.\n\"I thought I told you to stop smok\ning.\" said the doctor, severely.\n\"I tried to.\" replied the patient, \"foul\nI havn't the heart to disappoint the\nmembers of my family who look to me\nfor prize coupons and baseball pic\ntures.\" Washington ICvening Star.\n.Mrs. Kliza A. Itoby of Kocheport\nunderwent a serious operation fur\ncancer this morning at the Parker\nMemorial hospital.\nChoose\nGOLF\nTENNIS\nBASEBALL\nYou will find the Equipment you\nwant at the Missouri store.\nI'est Stove Casolene Iteid's Grocery.\nCasino at Lathrcp Open Tonight.\nFrom now on the Casino of l.athrop\nHallwill i;e open for dancing from\nii:-l until T:\"o each evening. The\nroom will be cooled with electric fans.\nTHE STOCK\nIS FRESH\nWELL ASSORTED\nAND EVERY\nARTICLE IS\nFULLY GUARANTEED\nISest Stove (lasolene Iteid's (Jro-\neery.\nnoiny is exercised. When the econo\nmies are resorted to the result is a\nhappy in'-rease in the aggregate cap\nital for investment. The old habits of\nexpenditure are promptly taken up. I\nwhen the fears pass by, ami the country\nrecuperates from itts depression with\nwonderful rapidity.\n\"The New Store With New Goods.\"\nCALIFORNIA CANTALOUPE SUNDAE 15c\nTHIS SALE Is Sweeping Everything Before it the imitation of competition is the sin\ncerest evidence that it has hit the mark the enthusiasm of the public is proof of its\nsuccess, as usual.\n17\nJilL\no\nAY\nU\nA\nW\nM\nTATORS\n345 3\nUIT\n2'jC\nZ5\nThe Dollar!\njWTO NEED to repeat the epoch making telegram that flashed over\nthe wires to the GLOBE the stir created by the publication has\nbeen as wide as the boundaries of the county itself. A lucky purchase\nfor us a lucky purchase for you. Buy your summer suit now and\nsave solidly\nONLY AT THE GLOBE!\nY4 h \"Is ILj\nSATURDAY ONLY\nFrom 10:30 a. m. to 9:30 p. m.\nNot a minute before or after.\n7C MEN'S AND\nYOUNG MEN'S\nSUITS $6.50\nValues positively $12.50 correct style, fine tailoring, and absolute genuine\nsatisfaction. Every suit